<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101795588884374></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101795588884374><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=101795588884374>RE: Feign Death</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=101795588884374#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=35651><span id=Guru>Keyeluke</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>590 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Apr 4th 4:31 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.80]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Instill doubt definitely works in PvP.&nbsp;&nbsp;A monk friend and I did a test, and he landed it on me quite effectively.  I took off running just like the mobs do :)<br><br>Reliability of FD... Hm.  I've never heard of a formula, just a bunch of speculation.  Against almost all mobs, at FD 200, I rarely get the 'fallen to the ground' message.  If I don't get the message and I dime it right with regard to spellcasters, I'm sitting pretty.  I have gotten the 'fallen to the ground' message at bad times.  I've also gotten it when I want to AFK and have nothing near me.  There is some speculation that it won't work as well if you're very low health, but no one's offered any substantive proof.<br><br>One thing that's a big question is when a mob ignores FD and keeps beating on you.  Some call it a bug, others consider it a game feature.  Many say it only happens against undead mobs or in certain zones.  However, it's something you won't encounter much at all till you get into your 50s, and even then you may never see it - so forget about it for now.<br><br>I've had FD maxed for it seems like forever.  It trains up faster as your skill goes up - same for ID.  Instill doubt is a very effective soloing tool in outdoor zones.  Land the ID, mob turns around and runs, you follow it beating on its back side.  I didn't really use it for this till I got into my upper 40s/lower 50s and had my skill maxed.  It got me lots of nice experience in Dreadlands fearing the dogs (they fear quite nicely) and in OOT on seafuries.  Actually, if you're in a group in an open area with a snarer, you can ID a mob and save healer mana - it'll turn and run snared, and you can all beat it up happily.<br><br>FD is your best friend.  Take the time to max it each level, and you'll more than recover that time in reduced corpse recoveries.  ID is situational.  In dungeons it's aptly nicknamed Instill Train, and I remove it from my hotkeys when I'm indoors.  Outdoors it's very useful in certain situations.<br>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke - <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a><br>Dripsy - <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=227922" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=227922</a></td></tr>
